CBRE Agribusiness is exceptionally proud to present for sale the Norman Farming holding – a large scale specialist irrigated and dryland cultivation operation – situated in the heart of the renowned Border Rivers Region of Queensland.

The amalgum of the “Kalanga” and “Mobandilla” Aggregations, the combined holding is one of the largest irrigated and dryland cropping enterprises on the East Coast of Australia, progressively assembled and developed to operate as a highly productive, single working enterprise.

Key investment highlights include:

- A combined land area of over 18,000* hectares, inclusive of over 5,100 hectares of highly developed flood irrigation, over 9,000 hectares of dryland cultivation, with the balance comprising water storage, grazing and support land.

- Significant water entitlements (Maximum Volumetric Limit of 76,000* megalitres, 7,000* megalitres take per day), including large nominal volumes of supplemented and unsupplemented allocations, overland flow and on-farm storages, all certified and licensed.

- High quality operational infrastructure, structural improvements, productive soil types and technological developments that enhance on-farm efficiencies.

- Productive capacity of over 40,000 bales of cotton, consistently yielding in excess of 12 bales per hectare, and 15,000 tonnes of chickpeas on the dryland.

- Excellent staff and management team, with Norman Farming having been recipients of the Australian Cotton Grower of the year in 2010, an ABC/Kondinin Group Australian Farmer of the Year 2011 finalist and an active proponent of industry best management practice programs.

- An unparalleled opportunity to acquire one of Australia’s most respected & highly regarded agricultural enterprises on a ‘Walk In Walk Out’ basis, inclusive of all land, structures, water licences, plant & equipment and planted crops.

Minmore Orchards located in Kumbia, Queensland, is an early market stone fruit operation comprising:

~ Two non-contiguous landholdings, totaling 294 hectares, comprising a 66 hectare stone fruit orchard, with the balance being grazing land.

~ The stone fruit orchard is currently planted to 34 hectares of various peach and nectarine varieties (approximately 22,500 trees).

~ High quality irrigation infrastructure with scope for further expansion.

~ An additional 11 hectares has been developed with irrigation infrastructure and is able to be planted to further expand the operation.

~ Structural improvements on the stone fruit orchard include two dwellings, cool room, workshop, machinery shed and garage.

~ The balance of the property is grazing land (approximately 228 hectares) and features a large irrigation dam, along with pumping infrastructure for the delivery of water to the stone fruit orchard.

~ Water security is a feature of Minmore Orchards. Water is supplied via a seasonal creek and a single equipped bore located on the grazing parcel. It must be noted that this bore is not located within a declared groundwater system and therefore does not have a volumetric cap.

For Sale by Expression of Interest closing Tuesday 16 December 2014 at 4.00pm (AEDT).

Inspections by appointment only.

CBRE Agribusiness are pleased to present Ausgold Aquaculture for sale, a substantial 79.25* hectare licensed freshwater fish farm located 65* kilometres south of Townsville, Queensland.

The facility was established in 1995 and has been producing quality Redclaw Crayfish for over twenty years. The farm was designed with the assistance of the Queensland Department of Primary Industries in accordance with best practice principles and is a closed recirculating system that uses low energy farming methods.

Ausgold Aquaculture implements flow trap harvesting which utilises the Redclaw’s natural instinct to move towards a flow of water and is a highly controllable method of harvesting.

Key investment highlights include: 

•	Currently, 30 ponds spanning 3* hectares with development approval granted for 80 ponds across 8* hectares and further growth opportunities presented by the potential expansion to 500 ponds across 50* hectares.
  
•	The facility’s licence has been granted in perpetuity to produce species including Australian Bass, Barcoo Grunter, Barramundi, Eel Tail Catfish, Freshwater Shrimp, Golden Perch, Gulf Saratoga, Murray Cod, Sleepy Cod, Southern Saratoga and Yabby.

•	Northern Australia’s climate and proximity to Asia are key factors in federal government plans to establish an export-focused food bowl. 

•	An unlimited supply of bore water, overland flow of 500* megalitres and a highly sought after 500* megalitre licence for the nearby Majors Creek.

•	Further sustainability is achieved through the use of effluent waters on surrounding hay paddocks, which in turn provide habitat and a supplementary feed source.

•	Improvements at the site include a 300* square metre, four-bedroom Queenslander cottage, a four-bay shed for fish packing, workshop, carport and an additional shed that would suit a hatchery.

•	With its location, cropping capabilities and water resources, the property would also lend itself to horticulture, hay-growing, spring water and tourism applications.

•	Excellent electricity infrastructure and supply with all equipment and plant enabling an immediate start to operations.
